HTTP vs HTTP/2 vs REST vs gRPC in Kubernetes

1. HTTP/1.1 vs HTTP/2 - The Evolution

HTTP/1.1 Problem

One request at a time. If first request is slow, all others wait. This is called Head-of-Line Blocking.
Opens a new connection for every request. Very heavy.

HTTP/2 Solution

Multiplexing: Many requests go together on one connection. No waiting.
Binary Format: Converts data to binary bits. Machines read it faster.

Real Benefit for IT Working

In Kubernetes, services talk faster. Less delay and less CPU usage on servers.

2. REST vs gRPC - API Design Styles

REST

Uses HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2
Uses JSON format (text)
Easy for humans to read
Works everywhere
Problem: JSON is heavy, eats more CPU and bandwidth

gRPC

Made by Google
Uses HTTP/2 only
Uses Protobuf (binary format)
5 times smaller than JSON
10 times faster than JSON
Has a strict contract file (.proto file) between services

Real Benefit for IT Working
Internal microservices in Kubernetes use gRPC to save network bandwidth and reduce CPU load.

3. Streaming in gRPC
Because of HTTP/2 and gRPC, you can do more than one request-response.

Four types of streaming:

Type	            How it works	                Example
Unary	            One request, one response	    Normal API call
Server Streaming	One request, many responses	  Live sports scores
Client Streaming	Many requests, one response	  Heavy file upload
Bidirectional     Streaming	Both send anytime   without waiting	Real time chat app

Real Benefit for IT Working
You can build live features without opening many connections. Log shipping and real time sync become easy.

4. How This Works Inside Kubernetes

A. Control Plane Communication
API Server, etcd, Scheduler, and Kubelet talk to each other using gRPC and Protobuf.
That is why kubectl commands and cluster updates happen instantly.

B. Ingress Controllers
External traffic comes in through Ingress (Nginx, Envoy, Traefik).
If your backend uses gRPC, you must configure Ingress for HTTP/2 and gRPC routing.
Normal HTTP/1.1 load balancers cannot handle gRPC because they cannot handle multiplexed single connections.

C. Service Mesh - The Multiplexing Savior
When hundreds of microservices talk to each other, opening separate connections for each destroys the network.
Service mesh like Istio or Linkerd automatically upgrades traffic to HTTP/2 multiplexing.
Thousands of requests travel on one connection without network lag.


Public facing traffic (browser to app) = REST + HTTP/2
Internal service to service in Kubernetes = gRPC + Protobuf
Control plane in Kubernetes = gRPC + Protobuf

Service mesh = automatically gives you HTTP/2 multiplexing
